1(ii)¶

In [12]:
# (ii) Perform dimensionality reduction using PCA
pca = PCA()
X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_scaled)

# Choose the optimal number of retained principal components
explained_variance_ratio = pca.explained_variance_ratio_
cumulative_variance = np.cumsum(explained_variance_ratio)
optimal_components = np.argmax(cumulative_variance >= 0.95) + 1

print(f"Optimal number of retained components: {optimal_components}")

Optimal number of retained components: 10

Choosing to retain components until 95% cumulative explained variance in PCA strikes a balance between preserving substantial information and reducing dimensionality. This threshold captures a significant portion of the dataset's variability in a more concise form, with adjustments possible based on analysis needs or desired information retention levels.

# (iv) Construct logistic regression model
pca = PCA(n_components=optimal_components)
X_train_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_pca = pca.transform(X_test)

model = LogisticRegression()
model.fit(X_train_pca, y_train)
y_pred = model.predict(X_test_pca)

# Evaluate the performance of the logistic regression model
accuracy = metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
print(f"Logistic Regression Accuracy: {accuracy}")

Logistic Regression Accuracy: 1.0

The output "Logistic Regression Accuracy: 1.0" indicates a flawless performance, with the logistic regression model achieving 100% accuracy on the test set, signifying perfect classification of all instances.

In this analysis, we developed regression models to understand agricultural yield under two distinct irrigation schemes. For Scheme 1, factors like soil quality, fertilizer amount, sunny days, and negative impact of rainfall influenced yield. Similarly, Scheme 2 highlighted the importance of these factors. The R-squared values of 0.72 and 0.70 for Schemes 1 and 2 indicated the models effectively explained a substantial portion of yield variance. Scatter plots visually confirmed the models' alignment with observed data, offering valuable insights for optimizing agricultural practices and enhancing food security.

Interpreting the model coefficients for each scheme revealed specific insights into the significance of factors. Soil quality, fertilizer amount, and sunny days had positive impacts on yield, while rainfall had a negative effect. These findings provide actionable information for farmers and stakeholders to make informed decisions regarding agricultural practices under different irrigation conditions. The R-squared values demonstrated the models' capability to capture underlying patterns, further supporting their reliability in explaining variations in agricultural yield.

Looking ahead, ongoing refinement and monitoring are crucial for adapting to changing environmental conditions or agricultural practices. This foundational regression analysis lays the groundwork for understanding and optimizing agricultural production, contributing to improved food security and supply chain management.

For an effective aid strategy, the United Nations should concentrate its efforts on a cluster of countries identified with low income and high mortality rates. Key socio-economic and health indices demanding attention include GDP per capita, infant mortality rate, access to clean water and sanitation, education levels, nutrition and food security, as well as disease prevention and vaccination coverage. Prioritizing these indices will allow the UN to address fundamental economic and health challenges, fostering sustainable development and improving the overall well-being of the targeted populations.
